The Federal Government has partially lifted the ban on interstate movement, even as it extended the second phase of the eased lockdown by another four weeks. Boss Mustapha, the Chairman of the Presidential Taskforce PTF on Covid-19, made the disclosure during the daily briefing in Abuja on Monday. Additionally, Mustapha announced that schools would re-open to allow final year students go back to classes within the extended phase. “I am pleased to inform you that Mr. President has carefully considered the 5th Interim Report of the PTF and has accordingly approved that, with the exception of some modifications to be expatiated upon later, the Phase Two of the eased lockdown be extended by another four weeks with effect from Tuesday, June 30, 2020, through Midnight of Monday, 27 July 2020. “Specifically, however, the following measures shall either remain in place or come into effect: Maintaining the current phase of the national response for another four weeks in line with modifications to be expatriated by the National Coordinator; Permission of movement across State borders only outside curfew hours with effect from 1st July 2020; Enforcement of laws around non-pharmaceutical interventions by States, in particular, the use of face masks in public places; Safe re-opening of schools to allow students in graduating classes resume in-person in preparation for examinations and; Safe reopening of domestic aviation services as soon as practicable”.